webpackJsonp([0x7761535c9b7f],{538:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{markdownRemark:{frontmatter:{title:"Debugging node.js in Cloud9 IDE",date:"2016-09-03T22:00:00.000Z",tags:["nodejs","JavaScript","Debugging"]},timeToRead:2,html:'<p>In this article I\'ll be sharing some of my level-up experience learning how to debug node.js apps. It was not easy at first, but once I got it, I felt empowered that now I can work with any code base.</p>\n<p>Debugging is useful for solving vague problems in other people\'s code and it\'s also useful for learning how something actually works. The article might be particularly useful for those used to having debugger experience in WebStorm or similar IDEs.</p>\n<h3 id="quick-reference"><a href="#quick-reference" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Quick reference</h3>\n<p>That article is meant to be more like a cheat sheet rather than too detailed step by step guide, here\'s a go-to list of techniques:</p>\n<h3 id="node-debugger"><a href="#node-debugger" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Node debugger</h3>\n<p>Let\'s start by the basics — using the <a href="https://nodejs.org/api/debugger.html">node\'s native debugger</a>.</p>\n<p>For example, <a href="https://github.com/Surnet/swagger-jsdoc/blob/master/example/app.js">this app</a> contains a simple server returning a JSON object which is a <a href="https://www.google.be/url?sa=t&#x26;rct=j&#x26;q=&#x26;esrc=s&#x26;source=web&#x26;cd=1&#x26;cad=rja&#x26;uact=8&#x26;ved=0ahUKEwiG4Pi0qfbOAhUEOhQKHaQICOAQFggcMAA&#x26;url=http%3A%2F%2Fswagger.io%2Fspecification%2F&#x26;usg=AFQjCNH_jZB7rkJVVCg-JHFmeLAHwMnUfw&#x26;sig2=R2rG7_9EH1ctFeFwtJ7cPw&#x26;bvm=bv.131783435,d.d24">swagger specification</a> and I need to debug and see its value. So, in this example, I\'ll follow this steps to see the contents of the variable:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Set a break point with <code class="language-text">debugger</code></li>\n<li>Run the script with <code class="language-text">node debug example/app.js</code></li>\n<li>Work with the controls of the debugger to reach a good value: <code class="language-text">c</code> to continue and <code class="language-text">n</code> for next</li>\n<li>Use <code class="language-text">repl</code> to execute some code which access current state of the system</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/1*CHRmYU912yZDRmqz7Z490w.gif"></p>\n<h3 id="simple-script"><a href="#simple-script" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Simple script</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Add a break point</li>\n<li>Press the Run button to execute the default node runner (ensure the debugger is enabled — <a href="https://docs.c9.io/docs/debugging-your-code">more info</a>)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/1*I-mVNLptBFDG-EaJpLR6rQ.gif"></p>\n<h3 id="mocha-tests"><a href="#mocha-tests" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Mocha tests</h3>\n<p>This is an <a href="https://docs.c9.io/docs/experimental-features">experimental feature</a>.</p>\n<p><img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/1*-8oDjYBTEU4-G8H5_vw5lg.png"></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Enable \'Tests" from the editor settings</li>\n<li>Refresh the page and see the panel</li>\n<li>Put a break point in the test</li>\n<li>Enable debugging in the "Test" panel</li>\n<li>Run the test suite or scenario</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This feature actually worked for me, I felt just the same way when I made my first <a href="http://mortalkombat.wikia.com/wiki/Animality">animality in MK3</a>.</p>\n<p><img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/1*OHINaf_jcvN75EN1M0ozlQ.gif"></p>\n<h3 id="command-line-apps"><a href="#command-line-apps" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Command-line apps</h3>\n<p>In fact it\'s almost identical to debugging a simple script, the only detail you have to notice is an input box where you put the actual command as if ran in the command line.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Open the command-line app and place a break point</li>\n<li>Use the Run menu to start the process in debug more</li>\n<li>Change the input process name and restart the runner</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/1*V9xHSnqzwCasqzHiHyBD5Q.gif"></p>'}},pathContext:{slug:"debugging-nodejs-in-cloud9-ide"}}}});
